General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (8) State agency or agency. – A State agency, department, or institution in the
2 executive or legislative branches of government or a political subdivision of
3 the State.
4 "§ 114-76. Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy.
5 (a) The Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy is created in the Department of Commerce.
6 The Secretary of Commerce shall appoint a Director to oversee the management and operations
7 of the office and adopt rules to carry out the purposes of this section.
8 (b) The purposes of the Office are to do all of the following:
9 (1) Identify regulatory barriers to artificial intelligence (AI) development,
10 deployment, and use in North Carolina and recommend regulatory proposals
11 to remove or avoid such barriers.
12 (2) Identify regulatory gaps where existing law is insufficient to prevent or redress
13 substantial, non-speculative, concrete, and redressable harm and recommend
14 regulatory proposals to fill such gaps.
15 (3) Conduct an inventory of existing State regulation of AI technology.
16 (4) Create and administer an Artificial Intelligence Learning Laboratory program.
17 (5) Consult with businesses and other stakeholders in the state about potential
18 regulatory proposals.
19 (6) Consult with Learning Laboratories or similar bodies in other states.
20 (7) Establish and convene a multidisciplinary AI Learning Advisory Panel
21 composed of academic experts, industry representatives, legal scholars, and
22 civil society organizations to provide input into the learning agenda and
23 ongoing evaluations.
24 (c) At a minimum, rules adopted under this Article shall concern the following:
25 (1) Procedures, requirements, and fees to apply to participate in the learning
26 laboratory program and criteria for invitation, acceptance, denial, or removal
27 of participants.
28 (2) Data usage limitations and cybersecurity criteria for participants.
29 (3) Required participant disclosures to consumers.
30 (4) Reporting requirements for participants to the Office.
31 (5) Criteria for limited extension of the participation period.
32 (6) Other requirements as necessary to administer the Learning Laboratory.
33 (c1) The Office shall maintain a public registry of Learning Laboratory participants and
34 publish summary reports of research findings, best practices, and policy recommendations,
35 excluding proprietary or security-sensitive information.
36 (d) Beginning July 1, 2026, the Office shall report annually to the General Assembly
37 about the following:
38 (1) The proposed learning agenda for the Learning Laboratory.
39 (2) The findings, participation, and outcomes of the Learning Laboratory.
40 (3) Recommended legislation from findings from the inventories and Learning
41 Laboratory.
42 (4) A review of the effectiveness of the Learning Laboratory model, and whether
43 any elements should be codified into permanent regulatory structures,
44 expanded, or sunset.
45 "§ 114-77. State AI inventory.
46 (a) By October 1, 2026, each State agency may compile, in a form specified by the Office,
47 an inventory of all artificial intelligence technologies that are in use by the State agency or being
48 developed or considered by the State agency for use. The inventory shall be submitted to the
49 Office, the Secretary of Commerce, the Governor, the Speaker of the House of Representatives,
50 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the Chairs and Ranking Minority Members of the
51 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations. By March 1, 2026, the Office may
