1 (1) Contents of Inventory. – The analysis conducted under this subsection shall
2 include all of the following:
3 a. A review of existing laws, regulations, executive orders, and state
4 agency rulemaking that pertain to the regulation of the development
5 and use of artificial intelligence technology within the State.
6 b. An assessment of the specific category of artificial intelligence use
7 governed by each existing law, regulation, executive order, and State
8 agency rulemaking, and whether each achieves its purpose without
9 impeding the development and use of artificial intelligence
10 technology.
11 c. An identification of any gaps where existing law, regulation, executive
12 order, and state agency rulemaking are insufficient to prevent or
13 redress substantial, non-speculative, concrete, and redressable harm
14 from a specific use of artificial intelligence technology.
15 d. An identification of state agencies that possess statutory authority to
16 regulate development and use of artificial intelligence technology.
17 (2) Submission of Analysis. – Upon completion of the analysis under this
18 subsection, the Office shall submit the findings to the Secretary of Commerce, the Governor, the
19 Speaker of the House of Representatives, the President of the Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the
20 Chairs and Ranking Minority Members of the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental
21 Operations.
22 "§ 114-78. AI Learning Laboratory Program.
23 (a) There is established the Artificial Intelligence Learning Laboratory Program, to be
24 administered by the Office. The purpose of the Learning Laboratory is to:
25 (1) Analyze and research the benefits, risks, impacts, and policy implications of
26 artificial intelligence technologies to inform the state regulatory framework.
27 (2) Encourage development of artificial intelligence technologies in the State.
28 (3) Evaluate the effectiveness and viability of current, potential, or proposed
29 regulation on artificial intelligence technologies in cooperation with artificial
30 intelligence developers.
31 (4) Produce findings and recommendations for legislation and regulation of
32 specific artificial intelligence uses.
33 (5) Analyze how AI technologies affect individual rights, fairness, and the public
34 interest, including impacts on protected classes and opportunities for bias
35 mitigation.
36 (b) The Office shall periodically set a learning agenda for the Learning Laboratory that
37 establishes the specific areas of artificial intelligence policy the office intends to study. The initial
38 learning agenda shall include identifying specific categories of artificial intelligence uses with
39 similar profiles of benefits, risks, impacts, and associated regulatory bodies. In establishing the
40 learning agenda, the office may consult with relevant agencies, industry leaders, academic
41 institutions in the State, and key stakeholders with relevant knowledge, experience, or expertise
42 in the area. The Office may invite and receive an application from a person to participate in the
43 Learning Laboratory. The Office shall establish the procedures and requirements for sending an
44 invitation and receiving requests to participate in the Learning Laboratory in accordance with the
45 purposes of the Learning Laboratory. Open-source projects shall be eligible for participation in
46 the Learning Laboratory. In selecting participants for the Learning Laboratory, the Office shall
47 consider each of the following:
48 (1) The relevance and utility of an invitee or applicant's artificial intelligence
49 technology to the learning agenda.
50 (2) The invitee or applicant's expertise and knowledge specific to the learning
51 agenda.
