General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Other factors identified by the Office as relevant to participation in the
2 Learning Laboratory.
3 (c) The Office shall work with participants to establish benchmarks and assess outcomes
4 of participation in the Learning Laboratory.
5 "§ 114-79. AI Learning Laboratory participation.
6 (a) The Office may approve an applicant to participate in the program. An approved
7 applicant becomes a participant by entering into a participation agreement with the Office and
8 relevant State agencies. Each participant shall provide required information to State agencies in
9 accordance with the terms of the participation agreement and report to the Office as required in
10 the participation agreement. A participant shall retain records as required by Office rule or the
11 participation agreement. A participant shall immediately report to the Office any incidents
12 resulting in consumer harm, privacy breach, or unauthorized data usage, which may result in
13 removal of the participant from the Learning Laboratory.
14 (b) A participant who uses or wants to utilize an artificial intelligence technology in the
15 State may apply for regulatory mitigation according to criteria and procedures outlined by the
16 Office by rule. The Office may grant, on a temporary basis, regulatory mitigation to a participant
17 by entering into a regulatory mitigation agreement with the Office and relevant agencies. To
18 receive regulatory mitigation, a participant must demonstrate that the applicant meets eligibility
19 criteria established under this Article. Any regulatory mitigation agreement between a participant
20 and the Office and relevant agencies shall specify limitations on scope of the use of the
21 participant's artificial intelligence technology, including (i) the number and types of users, (ii) ,
22 geographic limitations and other limitations to implementation, and (iii) safeguards to be
23 implemented any regulatory mitigation granted to the applicant. The Office shall consult with
24 relevant agencies regarding appropriate terms in a regulatory mitigation agreement. A participant
25 remains subject to all legal and regulatory requirements not expressly waived or modified by the
26 terms of the regulatory mitigation agreement. The Office may remove a participant at any time
27 and for any reason, and the participant does not have an expectation of a property right or license
28 to participate in the Learning Laboratory.
29 (c) A participant demonstrating an artificial intelligence technology that violates legal or
30 regulatory requirements (considering any regulatory mitigation agreement), or that violates the
31 terms of the participation agreement, may be immediately removed from further participation
32 and subject to all applicable civil and criminal penalties.
33 (d) Participation in the Learning Laboratory does not constitute an endorsement or
34 approval from the State.
35 (e) Participation or non-participation in the Learning Laboratory does not constitute a
36 legally cognizable factor for any tort claim, civil law violation, or criminal law violation.
37 (f) The State shall not be responsible for any claims, liabilities, damages, losses, or
38 expenses arising out of a participant's involvement in the learning laboratory.
39 "§ 114-80. Regulatory mitigation eligibility.
40 (a) To be eligible for regulatory mitigation, a participant shall demonstrate all of the
41 following to the Office:
42 (1) That the participant has the technical expertise and capability to responsibly
43 develop and test the proposed artificial intelligence technology.
44 (2) The participant has sufficient financial resources to meet obligations during
45 testing.
46 (3) The artificial intelligence technology provides potential substantial consumer
47 benefits that may outweigh identified risks from mitigated enforcement of
48 regulations.
49 (4) The participant has an effective plan to monitor and minimize identified risks
50 from testing.
Senate Bill 747-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) The scale, scope, duration of proposed testing is appropriately limited based
2 on risk assessments.
3 (6) For participants with fewer than 50 employees or under $10 million in annual
4 revenue, the Office may adjust eligibility or reporting requirements to reflect
5 organizational capacity, while ensuring appropriate risk controls.
6 (b) To evaluate whether an applicant meets eligibility criteria to receive regulatory
7 mitigation, the Office may consult with relevant agencies and outside experts regarding the
8 application.
9 (c) An initial regulatory mitigation agreement shall be in force for no longer than 12
10 months. A participant may request a single 12-month extension for participation in the Learning
11 Laboratory period no later than 30 days before the end of the initial 12-month period. The Office
12 shall grant or deny an extension request before expiration of the initial demonstration period."
13 SECTION 3. This act is effective when it becomes law.
